d on it for his own published account of the journey. Both the journal and Back's earlier notes have been edited by Houston, who provides an introduction and extensive annotations, as well as synopses of the frank comments regarding the expedition recorded in the various journals of the Hudson's Bay fur trade posts. I.S. MacLaren's commentary on Back's paintings reveals a midshipman-artist of exceptional talent. Conversant with the artistic conventions and aesthetic temper of his age, Back used his sketch-books not only to depict the expedition's progress but also to capture his imaginative response to the northern wilderness. MacLaren edits and comments on two other documents written by Back during the expedition: a candid letter to his brother and a poem dramatizing the disaster that claimed the lives of eleven of the twenty explorers in Franklin's party. Arctic Artist will be of interest to Franklin and Arctic enthusiasts, and to Canadian studies, northern studies, art history, and anthropology specialists.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aExplorerszGreat BritainxDiaries. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Post-Confederation (1867-).2bisacsh  afranklin.  alost expedition.  anorthwest passage.  apolar.1 aHouston, C. Stuart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHouston, C. Stuart, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMaclaren, I.S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356470140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773564701423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773564701/original  